==English==

{{rfc}} <!-- Webster's 1913 and 1828 definitions are highly superior to this.  Also,===Verb===is missing entirely! -->

===Adjective===

# of or relating to principles of [[right]] and [[wrong]] in behavior; as in ''moral judgments'' (see [[Ethical]])
# expressing or teaching a conception of right behavior; as in ''a moral poem''
# conforming to a standard of [[right]] behavior
# sanctioned by or operative on one's conscience or ethical judgment; as in  ''a moral obligation''
# capable of right and wrong action; as in ''a moral agent''

# probable but not proved; as in ''a moral certainty'' ( see [[Virtual]] )

# having the effects of such on the mind, confidence or will; as in ''a moral victory'' or ''moral support''

'''morally''' (adverb)

'''Synonyms:''' '''MORAL''' [[Ethical | ETHICAL]] [[Virtuous | VIRTUOUS]] [[righteous | RIGHTEOUS]] [[Noble | NOBLE]] mean conforming to a standard of what is [[right]] and [[good]].  MORAL implies conformity to established sanctioned codes or accepted notions of right and wrong; ETHICAL may suggest the involvement of more difficult or subtle questions or rightness, fairness, or equity; VIRTUOUS implies the possession or manifestation of moral excellence in character; RIGHTEOUS stresses guiltlessness or blamelessnes and often suggests the [[sanctimonious]]; NOBLE implies moral [[eminence]] and freedom from anything [[petty]], [[mean]] or [[dubious]] in conduct and character.

===Noun===
'''moral'''
# the moral significance or practical lesson (the moral of a story)

# moral practices or teachings: modes of conduct

# syn: [[Ethics]]

